We must also account for different orientations of the helical ordering vector ${{\bm q}}$. Minimizing the free energy for different orientations of ${\bm q}$ along high-symmetry directions relative to the 
deformation $\Phi_1({\bm k})=k_x^2-k_y^2$ \cite{qdirec}, we find that for all values of $T$ and $g$ over which fluctuations stabilize modulated order, the helical spin-triplet nematic with 
${\bm q}=q(1,1,0)/\sqrt{2}$ has the lowest free energy.

The region of superconducting order is calculated by assuming a continuous transition in the spin-nematic background using Eq.~(\ref{eq.FayAppel}). As noted in Section \ref{sec.pSc}, 
mode-mode coupling locks the orbital order in the relative orientation shown in Fig.~\ref{fig.orientation}. In the region of overlap between superconductivity and helical spin-triplet nematic order, 
the superconducting order parameter is locked to the helical spin nematic order and so displays a spatial modulation. 

