\subsection{Visualization in momentum- and real-space}

The helical spin-triplet nematic is not easy to visualize.  For small ${\bm q}$ vectors, corresponding to a long period of the 
modulation in real space, a Wigner representation as used in Fig.~\ref{fig.schematic} is the most convenient way to picture it. This is a mixed real/momentum space representation. 
Over a subsystem whose size is less then the wavelength of the modulation, the order is approximately uniform and one may define a quasi Fermi surface equivalent to that of the 
related homogeneous spin-triplet nematic.  The helical modulation in spin space implies that the spin direction rotates from sub-system to sub-systems with a period $2 \pi /q$. 

A purely momentum space picture of the spin-triplet nematic order is also useful as it helps reveal how spatial modulation might be favored by the softening of fluctuations. In 
Fig.~\ref{fig.momentum}, we show the Fermi surfaces $A_+$ and $A_-$ for the two electronic bands
 $\epsilon_\pm({\bm k})=k^2\mp\sqrt{({\bm k}.{\bm q})^2+\eta^2  \Phi_1^2({\bm k})}$, 
 with the wavevector ${{\bm q}}$ in the favored $(1,1,0)$ direction. $A_+$ and $A_-$ are the Fermi surfaces for electrons with spin parallel and anti-parallel to the background helimagnetic 
 ordering, respectively. In the limit ${\bm q}=0$, we recover the elliptical Fermi surfaces of the homogeneous spin-triplet nematic. These deformations of the Fermi surfaces change the spectrum of 
 electronic particle-hole excitations and enhance the phase space for fluctuations. 

